1
00:00:06,832 --> 00:00:09,654
Thank you for coming and choosing to listen to me.

2
00:00:09,674 --> 00:00:13,857
I'm Em, and I'm a sound designer at A Shell in the Pit Audio.

3
00:00:15,018 --> 00:00:18,140
And today I hope that I can help give some insight

4
00:00:18,300 --> 00:00:20,661
into how sound can help with storytelling.

5
00:00:21,382 --> 00:00:24,404
It's been the focus of my work for a while now,

6
00:00:24,744 --> 00:00:27,906
and I think it'd be great if everyone

7
00:00:28,386 --> 00:00:29,687
paid more attention to it.

8
00:00:32,239 --> 00:00:35,281
Night in the Woods was an inspiration to work on as a sound designer.

9
00:00:35,821 --> 00:00:41,585
The writers Scott Benson and Bethany Hockenberry included a whole bunch of sound into the story

10
00:00:42,005 --> 00:00:47,910
and Alec Holowka incorporated it into the music as a cohesive whole.

11
00:00:48,690 --> 00:00:49,331
Alec's right there.

12
00:00:52,426 --> 00:00:55,688
And Gordon Mclattery and Joey van Alden of A Shell in the Pit

13
00:00:56,028 --> 00:01:00,611
gave me a ton of support to explore, as well as actual

14
00:01:00,651 --> 00:01:04,513
sound and moral and creative support. Joey also did the

15
00:01:04,553 --> 00:01:08,635
sound for Demon Tower, the game within the game. So the sound

16
00:01:08,655 --> 00:01:12,137
design and these ideas I'll be sharing, were a collaboration

17
00:01:12,157 --> 00:01:19,481
between all of us. So this is a story about a place and a time.

18
00:01:20,278 --> 00:01:22,860
It's told through setting, atmosphere, and characters.

19
00:01:23,581 --> 00:01:25,963
And my goal with the sound was to reflect this

20
00:01:26,163 --> 00:01:27,744
and bring you closer into the setting

21
00:01:28,224 --> 00:01:30,186
to make you feel as though you are May

22
00:01:30,986 --> 00:01:32,647
feeling as she would feel in this place.

23
00:01:33,448 --> 00:01:37,031
And so every one of the 5,090 sounds in the game

24
00:01:37,491 --> 00:01:39,072
make a contribution to the story.

25
00:01:39,953 --> 00:01:43,115
Even with the foley, Scott gave me the direction

26
00:01:43,155 --> 00:01:45,697
to make May's footsteps and cloth sound

27
00:01:45,777 --> 00:01:48,459
as if she were an ungraceful potato sack.

28
00:01:51,618 --> 00:01:57,501
So these two television characters also add by helping establish the mood in this opening scene.

29
00:01:58,742 --> 00:02:03,824
Even without looking at the dialogue, things feel a little bit ridiculous and a little bit off.

30
00:02:04,985 --> 00:02:11,488
There are awkward silences, laughter, clapping, all entwined with the voices to make it feel alive.

31
00:02:16,751 --> 00:02:19,932
Being alive in terms of sound means chaos.

32
00:02:21,217 --> 00:02:24,439
It means that if there is a repetitive action, like this conversation,

33
00:02:25,099 --> 00:02:28,761
there will be a corresponding set of variable sounds that trigger randomly.

34
00:02:30,702 --> 00:02:33,964
Being alive also means rhythm and movement in everything.

35
00:02:35,104 --> 00:02:39,186
It means that sound comes from both known and unknown sources.

36
00:02:44,245 --> 00:02:47,686
That sense of liveliness is all bundled up under the umbrella of

37
00:02:47,746 --> 00:02:53,827
feeling. To be alive is to feel so everything inside every scene

38
00:02:53,907 --> 00:02:58,708
has its own mood. How do you feel about being here? And why?

39
00:02:58,728 --> 00:03:08,210
I made each different ambience by taking the feelings Scott's

40
00:03:08,290 --> 00:03:10,270
art gave me and giving them voice.

41
00:03:12,639 --> 00:03:16,601
Literally, what better way to convey a sense of life than

42
00:03:16,662 --> 00:03:19,624
human breath. So I use my own voice for a lot of the sound

43
00:03:19,664 --> 00:03:23,246
effects and ambiences. I made most of the wind sounds by

44
00:03:23,447 --> 00:03:27,790
blowing into the microphone like this, and cutting them into

45
00:03:27,850 --> 00:03:31,312
short segments that faded in and out and turning it into a

46
00:03:31,392 --> 00:03:34,395
scatterer ambience, which is a sound that gets triggered at

47
00:03:34,435 --> 00:03:38,498
random time intervals, as well as a random position in space.

48
00:03:40,459 --> 00:03:43,583
I used this particular layer as an element in almost every

49
00:03:43,663 --> 00:03:47,928
outdoor scene to create a persistent lonely atmosphere. And

50
00:03:47,948 --> 00:03:51,792
I reuse signature or thematic sounds a lot because I find it

51
00:03:51,832 --> 00:03:56,417
helps in manipulating you subconsciously. Also, this was

52
00:03:56,537 --> 00:03:59,861
our implementation tool of choice f mod, not going to talk

53
00:03:59,881 --> 00:04:00,762
too much about it, though.

54
00:04:02,869 --> 00:04:06,351
So here the fireflies change from fluttering to chirping

55
00:04:06,532 --> 00:04:07,712
when you jump into a swarm,

56
00:04:07,953 --> 00:04:09,193
like they're excited to be with you.

57
00:04:09,954 --> 00:04:12,175
They react both visually and audibly.

58
00:04:13,817 --> 00:04:16,999
So in the real world, we react to things as they happen.

59
00:04:17,719 --> 00:04:18,580
They give us memories.

60
00:04:18,840 --> 00:04:20,341
We live with all of our senses.

61
00:04:21,322 --> 00:04:23,743
So having a character react to a sound

62
00:04:23,803 --> 00:04:25,485
at the same time you're experiencing it

63
00:04:25,645 --> 00:04:28,126
makes it feel as though all the elements belong together.

64
00:04:29,110 --> 00:04:30,951
like this is a real world.

65
00:04:31,611 --> 00:04:33,872
I was pretty excited to discover moments like this

66
00:04:33,933 --> 00:04:34,733
throughout the script.

67
00:04:36,994 --> 00:04:39,856
And a fun fact is that the sound of one firefly

68
00:04:39,916 --> 00:04:41,777
is actually the sound of a bunch of frogs.

69
00:04:45,839 --> 00:04:49,561
So in this real world, the characters have their own agency.

70
00:04:50,116 --> 00:04:52,236
This ambience was one of the first ones I made.

71
00:04:52,256 --> 00:04:55,857
I wanted to give Mae's home a comforting sense of life.

72
00:04:56,157 --> 00:04:59,018
And so I decided this meant waking up and hearing your mom

73
00:04:59,478 --> 00:05:01,379
bustling around downstairs and humming.

74
00:05:02,479 --> 00:05:04,159
Later in the process, Alec pointed out

75
00:05:04,259 --> 00:05:05,640
that it didn't make too much sense

76
00:05:06,060 --> 00:05:07,200
because when you go downstairs,

77
00:05:07,300 --> 00:05:08,720
Mae's mom is just sitting there reading.

78
00:05:09,880 --> 00:05:11,021
But instead of taking it out,

79
00:05:11,081 --> 00:05:13,621
I decided to create a little narrative each morning

80
00:05:13,981 --> 00:05:16,782
and have Mae's mom finish up and sit down

81
00:05:18,342 --> 00:05:19,663
right as you come down the stairs.

82
00:05:20,757 --> 00:05:23,858
So this is an example of a sound coming from an unknown source

83
00:05:24,178 --> 00:05:27,999
as and it also has the special purpose of letting you know that

84
00:05:28,459 --> 00:05:35,902
she's there to talk to if you want. Where is Angus off to?

85
00:05:40,324 --> 00:05:44,789
Yes, grabbing the USB stick he has handy under a couple pieces of paper on his desk.

86
00:05:45,670 --> 00:05:50,114
Off screen sound can really help if you don't have enough time to animate everything and

87
00:05:50,134 --> 00:05:52,777
it doesn't have to be something that was left out, it can be a choice.

88
00:05:53,792 --> 00:05:56,194
That rummaging sound only took a couple minutes to make,

89
00:05:56,494 --> 00:05:58,376
so you can really use that to your advantage.

90
00:05:59,157 --> 00:06:00,718
If you're a writer, you can plan for it,

91
00:06:00,958 --> 00:06:02,099
and if you're a sound designer,

92
00:06:02,620 --> 00:06:04,341
you can look carefully for those moments

93
00:06:04,502 --> 00:06:07,965
where you can add continuing movement and fluidity

94
00:06:08,365 --> 00:06:10,147
and connect little narrative threads.

95
00:06:12,449 --> 00:06:14,571
And it doesn't have to be an obvious action either.

96
00:06:15,594 --> 00:06:18,435
Just like May's house, this location has its own story,

97
00:06:19,135 --> 00:06:20,916
and we can hear the neighbors, which

98
00:06:20,976 --> 00:06:23,416
hints that Angus and his partner Greg

99
00:06:23,456 --> 00:06:26,297
live in a less than ideal location with thin walls.

100
00:06:27,117 --> 00:06:29,178
And it tells us that they live among people who

101
00:06:29,218 --> 00:06:31,099
are living their own story.

102
00:06:31,259 --> 00:06:34,159
They're watching a movie, and it's

103
00:06:34,219 --> 00:06:35,680
outside of what we're experiencing

104
00:06:35,800 --> 00:06:36,880
with the main characters.

105
00:06:40,482 --> 00:06:45,187
So we come back to the town every day, so it was important to enhance that sense of

106
00:06:45,247 --> 00:06:45,888
liveliness.

107
00:06:46,969 --> 00:06:51,734
The telephone wires respond to us, sounding higher in pitch in the end and lower in the

108
00:06:51,774 --> 00:06:55,158
middle, and they have a higher probability of rattling in the middle.

109
00:07:01,140 --> 00:07:03,381
Everything we can jump on responds to us differently.

110
00:07:04,101 --> 00:07:05,742
The squirrels react to the environment

111
00:07:05,802 --> 00:07:07,383
outside of what the player is doing,

112
00:07:07,923 --> 00:07:09,784
filling the landscape with little footsteps

113
00:07:09,884 --> 00:07:10,885
on each different surface.

114
00:07:11,826 --> 00:07:14,167
And to achieve this effect, I took a little rock

115
00:07:14,507 --> 00:07:17,188
and tapped it against some concrete or a chair

116
00:07:17,409 --> 00:07:18,729
or my guitar strings,

117
00:07:18,769 --> 00:07:20,690
which is what the telephone wires are made of.

118
00:07:22,271 --> 00:07:26,113
And I also made the car sounds using a highly advanced

119
00:07:26,233 --> 00:07:28,575
and unique process, which I will demonstrate now.

120
00:07:38,333 --> 00:07:41,935
The main town ambience is filled with randomly triggering sounds.

121
00:07:42,716 --> 00:07:46,918
The train from earlier passing by every 90 to 300 seconds.

122
00:07:47,738 --> 00:07:52,121
Townspeople that we can't see are calling out to one another and we've got the wind

123
00:07:52,221 --> 00:07:55,303
and birds chirping between one to three seconds.

124
00:07:58,470 --> 00:08:01,930
Each different time interval was a deliberate choice that said something.

125
00:08:06,352 --> 00:08:14,153
So this is a kind of a silly detail, but the pigeons have a 44% chance of pecking a seed

126
00:08:14,674 --> 00:08:16,334
and a lower chance of breaking it open.

127
00:08:22,835 --> 00:08:27,558
It seems minute, but adding probability helps make the world sound less repetitive.

128
00:08:28,539 --> 00:08:32,582
And as creators of this world, we never know how intimate you're going to get with any

129
00:08:32,602 --> 00:08:33,362
given space.

130
00:08:38,326 --> 00:08:43,490
I did all this detail to help sell the idea, again, that you are May, and you're waking

131
00:08:43,570 --> 00:08:46,212
up every day and moving through this ever-changing town.

132
00:08:47,072 --> 00:08:48,794
And it does change visually as well.

133
00:08:49,154 --> 00:08:51,095
Everything is centered around the passing of time.

134
00:08:52,197 --> 00:08:55,981
So if you decide to stand in one place for a while, you'll hear more than a loop.

135
00:08:56,481 --> 00:09:03,569
The ambiances were designed to situate you in time and in the spirit of the many procedural visuals are always random.

136
00:09:06,692 --> 00:09:10,116
So ambiances were really important in the sound design of this game.

137
00:09:11,280 --> 00:09:14,441
Each different atmosphere was another opportunity for immersion.

138
00:09:15,101 --> 00:09:20,982
Whether it's hissing pipes passing by, a reverb that suggests a deep, dark tunnel, or a chef

139
00:09:21,222 --> 00:09:23,423
who's humming along to the background music every day.

140
00:09:24,483 --> 00:09:28,904
We took all the opportunities we could think of to blend sound effects and music together.

141
00:09:28,924 --> 00:09:29,664
Like here.

142
00:09:32,059 --> 00:09:36,222
Alec, who is the composer, asked for the sound of the train to

143
00:09:36,262 --> 00:09:40,265
have the same BPM as the music. The sound effect actually made

144
00:09:40,285 --> 00:09:50,433
it onto the soundtrack, which I was pretty excited about. And

145
00:09:50,453 --> 00:09:54,055
we often used a real time parameter control to determine

146
00:09:54,115 --> 00:09:57,358
how sounds change based on the game state or your actions.

147
00:09:58,392 --> 00:10:06,719
So in this case, I like the idea that as you climb higher in the town, the wind builds up and the music loses its low frequencies and gets quieter.

148
00:10:07,980 --> 00:10:15,026
So this bottom track is a gradual high-pass filter and the two top tracks are the wind fading in.

149
00:10:18,029 --> 00:10:23,433
So once you get to the top, you can hear once again that lonely wind and it creates a moment for me.

150
00:10:24,497 --> 00:10:26,819
It feels different than standing on the street like you've

151
00:10:26,859 --> 00:10:30,142
accomplished something. And you can listen to the pigeons

152
00:10:30,242 --> 00:10:31,083
finding seeds.

153
00:10:36,247 --> 00:10:39,510
Similarly, when you walk into a store, the music is different

154
00:10:39,530 --> 00:10:43,152
than on the street. It is diegetic, which means that it

155
00:10:43,193 --> 00:10:45,614
exists for the characters and the story as a part of their

156
00:10:45,675 --> 00:10:49,097
world. And so here it sounds as if it's coming from the

157
00:10:49,117 --> 00:10:50,238
speakers in this location.

158
00:10:51,531 --> 00:10:54,473
Which if it interests you, I made happen with a convolution

159
00:10:54,513 --> 00:10:58,755
reverb called fog convolver, a little bit of EQ and some delay.

160
00:11:03,117 --> 00:11:06,679
Diegetic music can really help create moments and affect mood.

161
00:11:07,100 --> 00:11:11,002
So here May and her friend B are having an argument. In the

162
00:11:11,042 --> 00:11:13,623
middle of the conversation, the record that was playing fades

163
00:11:13,723 --> 00:11:17,625
out, and you're left hearing the needle. It makes things serious

164
00:11:17,785 --> 00:11:18,446
and uncomfortable.

165
00:11:19,930 --> 00:11:22,831
And sometimes silence is more powerful than music.

166
00:11:23,831 --> 00:11:26,632
And it can make music more meaningful in contrast.

167
00:11:26,912 --> 00:11:29,572
So we should try to avoid carpet bombing our stories

168
00:11:29,612 --> 00:11:31,253
with music, even if it's super good.

169
00:11:31,533 --> 00:11:33,613
I think that we should choose our moments for both.

170
00:11:37,674 --> 00:11:39,794
We can also get creative with how we transition

171
00:11:39,834 --> 00:11:40,895
from one song to another.

172
00:11:41,055 --> 00:11:43,755
So how would someone playing obnoxious guitar

173
