00:16:50,329 --> 00:16:53,891
use some of these sounds as scatterers. So they behave just

246
00:16:53,931 --> 00:16:59,254
like the wind I talked about before. And I did in a few

247
00:16:59,354 --> 00:17:01,576
cases add too much detail.

248
00:17:02,085 --> 00:17:04,765
and had to scale back for performance issue reasons.

249
00:17:05,626 --> 00:17:07,286
So if I did it again, I would start

250
00:17:07,366 --> 00:17:09,267
by making the ambiences more condensed,

251
00:17:09,607 --> 00:17:11,487
but it was a learning process.

252
00:17:14,288 --> 00:17:16,248
So my interpretation of this dream

253
00:17:16,609 --> 00:17:18,609
is that a tear is made in the universe,

254
00:17:19,089 --> 00:17:21,290
and it unleashes all the horrible sounds that

255
00:17:21,330 --> 00:17:25,371
continue to pop up after this, as if it breaks open May's head

256
00:17:26,491 --> 00:17:28,032
and leaves a portal to this dimension.

257
00:17:28,566 --> 00:17:32,088
which is why I added all those ambient layers to this big, important moment.

258
00:17:32,988 --> 00:17:34,529
So you make those associations. ♪♪

259
00:17:46,135 --> 00:17:49,376
And this breathing track that comes in now was actually an accident,

260
00:17:49,436 --> 00:17:52,738
where for some reason the track and the event itself didn't fade out

261
00:17:52,778 --> 00:17:55,079
with the rest of the sound between scene transitions.

262
00:17:56,274 --> 00:18:02,237
But I think sometimes accidents and the randomness of the system kind of work and I ended up quite liking that effect

263
00:18:05,599 --> 00:18:12,302
So I took those signature sounds from the dreams and placed them at moments in the story in the real world that meant something

264
00:18:13,123 --> 00:18:14,403
To emphasize a connection

265
00:18:15,284 --> 00:18:22,287
I added the sound whenever a particular being is around and made it get louder the longer you stay there using an AD HSR

266
00:18:23,290 --> 00:18:27,452
And I imagined again that it's coming from Mae's head as if you're hearing what she's hearing.

267
00:18:28,632 --> 00:18:32,294
And I didn't do any of this imagining that you would think about it consciously.

268
00:18:33,274 --> 00:18:36,855
But I think that just because something is unconsciously noticed doesn't mean it's not

269
00:18:36,875 --> 00:18:41,417
working as a functional part of the story. And it doesn't mean it's not noticed at all.

270
00:18:42,217 --> 00:18:47,319
Sound is an emotion. It's an intangible feeling. And we notice the feelings it gives us.

271
00:18:48,692 --> 00:18:50,172
Even if we don't pinpoint the source.

272
00:18:51,173 --> 00:18:54,594
I didn't find that discouraging, but I find it powerful.

273
00:18:55,474 --> 00:18:57,155
One of my least favorite expressions

274
00:18:57,255 --> 00:18:58,976
in the sound design industry is that

275
00:18:59,636 --> 00:19:01,777
if you've done a good job, people won't notice.

276
00:19:02,097 --> 00:19:06,159
And I would argue that we shouldn't seek to go unnoticed,

277
00:19:06,259 --> 00:19:09,260
but instead to provoke people into listening

278
00:19:09,320 --> 00:19:10,641
by making them feel shit.

279
00:19:14,643 --> 00:19:16,564
And sometimes the game can respond to the sound.

280
00:19:16,784 --> 00:19:21,946
I implemented that signature sound idea and was surprised and super excited to discover

281
00:19:21,986 --> 00:19:23,846
it written into the story later on.

282
00:19:37,771 --> 00:19:42,933
I got this idea to try to affect you emotionally with a signature sound from inside.

283
00:19:43,555 --> 00:19:48,078
I was terrified by the horrible water demon in that game, and I realized that I could

284
00:19:48,118 --> 00:19:53,201
tell when it was near because it would play an ominous musical tone, which I first noticed

285
00:19:53,221 --> 00:19:58,524
when I approached a hatch, and it had been placed there as a spot ambience, and I felt

286
00:19:58,564 --> 00:19:59,184
fear building.

287
00:19:59,964 --> 00:20:03,166
And I didn't want to open the door and confront the creature, and he would be there.

288
00:20:03,186 --> 00:20:05,988
I spent a long time just standing there.

289
00:20:06,700 --> 00:20:08,481
And it made a huge emotional impact.

290
00:20:08,761 --> 00:20:11,022
So whenever May is approaching something dark,

291
00:20:11,102 --> 00:20:13,223
the volume of the horrible sound is increased

292
00:20:13,243 --> 00:20:13,983
the closer you get.

293
00:20:14,764 --> 00:20:17,825
I wanted to make you uneasy and reluctant to move forward.

294
00:20:18,966 --> 00:20:21,387
So when May starts out on the right in this scene,

295
00:20:21,467 --> 00:20:22,767
